no o ka maʻi e hana ai i kēlā mea.  Hele mai ka poʻe i koʻu hale,\n57:18 mk:MK: {Mū.}\n57:18 HA: a, kēlā, he kumu pū hala, mamake lākou i kēlā mea, kēlā a o ka hala, kēlā mea,\n57:25 mk:MK: ʻĒ.\n57:25 HA: e ulu mai ana, ē?  A ulu mai, a, a, a ka, o ka aʻa.  Ma laila, mamake lākou i kēlā mea.  He lāʻau kēlā.\n57:33 mk:MK: ʻAe.\n57:34 HA: A hana lākou, ʻaʻole wau i nīnau, he aha lā ka ʻano maʻi e hoʻohana ʻia ai kēia, kēia lāʻau, kēia mea o ka hala.  Kaʻu ʻike, kaʻu mea ʻike no ka poʻe maʻi, a,\n57:50 mk:MK: A, a, akā, ua lohelohe au no ka, no ka wahine hānau paha.\n57:55 HA: ʻO ia?\n57:56 mk:MK: E, ʻae, e hoʻoikaika ana iā ia, iā loko o ke kino.\n57:59 HA: ʻAe.\n58:00 mk:MK: ʻO ia koʻu mea i, i lohelohe ai.\n58:02 HA: ʻŌ.\n58:03 mk:MK: A ʻo ia koʻu mea hoʻi i kāhea aku nei iā ʻoe.\n58:06 HA: Yeah.\n58:06 mk:MK: Mahalo kēia hui ʻana me ʻoe.\n58:08 HA: ʻAe.  Mahalo, a ʻanoʻai kāua.\n58:09 mk:MK: A, aloha aku iā,\n58:11 HA: ʻAe.\n58:12 mk:MK: Kauanoe.\n58:12 HA: ʻAe.\n58:13 mk:MK: A hoʻomaikaʻi au iā ʻolua no kā ʻolua mau hana maikaʻi.\n58:16 HA: ʻAe.\n58:16 mk:MK: A hui hou aku nō.\n58:17 HA: A hui hou.\n58:18 mk:MK: ʻAe.\n58:18 HA: ʻAe.\n58:18 mk:MK:  Aloha.\n58:19 HA: Aloha.\n58:21 LK: ʻAe.  ʻO ia wale ihola ka manawa o kēia ahiahi.  Ua pau ko mākou hola no kēia manawa.  Ma mua nō naʻe o ka hoʻopau ʻana, makemake nui koʻu e mahalo aku i ka poʻe i hana, kōkua mai no kēia papahana.  ʻO Pat, a, Unabia, ka mea e haʻi ana ma ka ʻōlelo Hawa^^ a, haole.  A, nā mea hoʻokani pila, ʻo Lorna and Mikala McClellen, Kuʻuleimomo Bernardino, Momilani Kalāʻaukahi, Eldon Akamine, Kaniela Akaka.  A ʻo nā mea e kamaʻilio ana no ka mokupuni o Maui, ʻo Mikahala Achan, me Kaniela Akaka.  A ʻo ka mea e haʻiʻōlelo ana, i haʻiʻōlelo no ka, no nā iʻa ʻono o ka ʻāina, ʻo Ed Lampsly.  A me nā ʻōlelo aloha, ʻo Kalena Silva.  A me nā mea ʻelua i hoʻoholo mai i kēia poʻe mīkini o kēia ahiahi, ʻo Eldon Akamine, me Harold, ke keiki hoʻolele leo o KCCN.  No laila, aloha a nui loa iā ʻoukou a pau loa, a hui hou aku kākou.\n59:36 HB  #Those interested in pursuing Hawaiian language and culture, can write the Hawaiian language for Department at University of Hawaiʻi.  Hawaiʻi is yours and mine, our only home.  Let''s live our Hawaiian culture.\n59:49  Hawaiʻi Aloha \n59:56 KS ## ʻAnoʻai ke aloha e nā pua o ka ʻāina.  Ua pā iho nei ko ʻoukou mau pepeiao i Ka Leo Hawaiʻi o ke ahiahi a me nā mele aloha o ka ʻāina, me he kahawai lā, e ʻōlino mau, e nanahe mau, a e nani mau.  Aloha a nui loa iā ʻoukou a pau, a hui hou aku kākou.\n > E Hawaiʻi e kuʻu one hānau ē, hānau ē\n Kuʻu home kulaiwi nei\n ʻOli nō au i nā pono lani ou, lani ou\n E Hawaiʻi aloha ē\n\n E hauʻoli e nā ʻōpio Hawaiʻi nei\n ʻOli ē, ʻoli ē, ʻoli ē, ʻoliʻoli ē\n Mai nā aheahe makani e pā mai nei, pā mai nei\n61:31 Mau ke aloha no Hawaiʻi',TRUE,'2023-08-06 20:18:20','2023-08-20 13:43:53.407997');
INSERT INTO articles VALUES(11,1,21,'5d468565-e44d-4308-ac6c-2896b0b2e341','Ka Leo Hawaiʻi 003: Louis Kaulanaʻula Grace  (1972-03-28)','00:00 # Beginning of Hawaiian tape HV24 reel 3.\n00:07 Hui Aloha ʻĀina Tuahine\n  > Hui Aloha ʻĀina Tuahine he inoa\n  Hui Aloha ʻĀina Tuahine, ʻeā ʻeā\n  Ka hui nō ka ʻoi ma ke kulanui o Hawaiʻi\n  Hui Aloha ʻĀina Tuahine, ʻeā ʻeā\n\n00:48 KS ## ʻAuhea ʻoukou e nā makamaka.  E hoʻolohe mai iā mākou, nā ʻōpio o ke Kulanui o Hawaiʻi.  E lohe ana ʻoukou i nā mea e pili ana i nā hana, a me nā ʻike o nā kūpuna i aloha nui ʻia.  E hoʻolele ana Ka Leo Hawaiʻi i nā Poʻalua o kēlā me kēia pule ʻelua.  E hoʻomaka ana kēia hoʻolele leo i\n01:23 kēia manawa, ka hola ʻewalu o ke ahiahi.\n01:24 h:HB @ Welcome to Ka Leo Hawaiʻi.  In this evening''s presentation of Ka Leo Hawaiʻi, students will participate in two dialogues.  The first involves a young lady just back from the island of Kauaʻi and a friend of hers.  Their discussion centers on her trip and the various attractions of Kauaʻi.  The second dialogue was especially written for a song entered by the Hui Aloha ʻĀina Tuahine in the Department of Parks and Recreation Hawaiian Song Contest.  The story involves a girl and a boy and an experience of theirs with the thorny kolū bush.  The first dialogue will be accompanied by songs about the island of Kauaʻi, and the second by the student''s composition, Ka Pua Kolū Nani Loa.  The guest for tonight''s live section is Reverend Louis Grace, a native of Nāpoʻopoʻo, South Kona.\n02:17 Nani Waiʻaleʻale\n  > Kaulana wale ʻoe Kauaʻi\n  Kuahiwi nani Waiʻaleʻale\n  A me nā kini, ʻeā\n  Manokalanipō\n   \n  Kaulana wale ʻoe Kauaʻi\n  Kuahiwi nani Waiʻaleʻale\n  A me nā kini, ʻeā\n  Manokalanipō\n\n  He moani aʻe nei ke ʻala\n  O ka mokihana me ka lauaʻe\n  A me nā pua, ʻeā\n  Like ʻole o ka ʻāina\n\n  He moani aʻe nei ke ʻala\n  O ka mokihana me ka lauaʻe\n  A me nā pua, ʻeā\n  Like ʻole o ka ʻāina\n\n  Kuʻina i nākolo i nā pali\n  I ka wai aʻo Nāmolokama\n  A me nā limu, ʻeā\n  E pakika o Manuʻakepa\n\n  Kuʻina i nākolo i nā pali\n  I ka wai aʻo Nāmolokama\n  A me nā limu, ʻeā\n  E pakika o Manuʻakepa\n\n  Hāʻina ʻia mai ka puana\n  Kuahiwi nani Waiʻaleʻale\n  A me nā kini, ʻeā\n  Manokalanipō\n\n  Hāʻina ʻia mai ka puana\n  Kuahiwi nani Waiʻaleʻale\n  A me nā kini, ʻeā\n  Manokalanipō\n\n04:52 h:PN  Ka Mokupuni ʻO Kauaʻi:\n E Kaipo, ʻaʻala kou lei mokihana me ka maile lau liʻi.  Ma hea mai kēnā lei uʻi?\n05:03 h:h1 ʻAkahi nō wau a hoʻi mai mai Kauaʻi mai.  Naʻu i kiʻi i kēia lei mai Kōkeʻe mai.\n05:10 h:PN Pehea?  Ua mālie ʻo Kōkeʻe?\n05:13 h:h1 ʻAʻole.  ʻAno uhiwai nō.  Akā, ua ʻike lihi au iā Kalalau me ke awāwa nani o Waimea.\n05:23 h:PN Ua lohe aku nei ʻoe i ke kani walu honehone a ka moa?\n05:27 h: h1 ʻAe.  I kuʻu iho ʻana i kai, ʻike wau i nā moa e ʻai ana i ka palama ma ka ʻaoʻao o ke alanui.  A hālō aʻe wau iā Niʻihau i ka ʻehu kai.\n05:39 h:PN Ua iho ʻoe i kai o hea?\n05:42 h:h1 U^^, ua hōʻea wau i ke one kani o Nohili me Polihale i ka pahapaha lei.  Ma laila aku, hele aku wau i Waimea.\n05:52 h:PN A, ma Waimea i kū mua ai ʻo Kāpena Kuke.  Ua ʻike aku ʻoe i ka ʻāina hānau o Kūhiō Kalanianaʻole?\n06:01 h:h1 ʻAe.  Mahalo au i ka nani o Poʻipū me Kukuiʻula, kahi hānau o Kūhiō.  Nanea wau i ke kaha nalu o ia kaha.\n06:11 h:PN Nani mai hoʻi kau ʻo Hāʻena me nā pali.\n06:14 h:h1 Pololei.  I koʻu hele ʻana i kēlā ʻaoʻao, hele wāwae au i Hanakāpīʻai.  Nui ka ʻōpae, ka ʻoʻopu, ka wī me ka ʻōhiʻa ʻai.\n06:26 h:PN He mau ana nui ko Hāʻena.  He ana wai kekahi, a he ana maloʻo kekahi.  Auē hoʻi ka nani o Hanalei.  A pehea ka nani o Hanalei iā ʻoe?\n06:38 h:h1 Aloha wau i ke kūʻono laulā.  He ʻāina ulu kalo ʻo Hanalei no ka lawa pono o ka ua.  Kaulana ʻo Hanalei i ka ua loku.\n06:49 h:PN Kūkilakila ka hale ipu kukui i ka lae ʻo Kīlauea me ke kai hānupanupa a me nā manu ʻā e pōʻai ana.  Aia hoʻi ma Kīlauea kekahi paheʻe wai i hana ʻia no ke kiʻiʻoniʻoni ʻo South Pacific. Aia i uka i ke kuahiwi.  He wahi i kapa ʻia ʻo Waipaheʻe.  Na ka wai i hana kēia paheʻe wai.  A na ke kanaka i hana ka pahe^^ (paheʻe) wai ʻo Kīlauea.\n07:15 h:h1 ʻOluʻolu nō koʻu holo wai ʻana ma ka muliwai ʻo Wailua a hiki i ka pae ʻana i ke ana kupukupu.\n07:23 h:PN ʻO Wailua kahi i hānai ʻia ai ʻo Kawelo, ʻeā?\n07:27 h:h1 ʻAe, ʻoiaʻiʻo nō.  A aia ma uka o ka heiau ʻo Holoholokū, nā pōhaku kāni^^ (kani).  ʻŌlelo ʻia i ka wā kahiko, hoʻokani ʻia nā pōhaku i mea hoʻolono no ka poʻe o Wailua.  Eia he wahi mea ʻono kuki macadamia nāu mai Līhuʻe mai.\n07:49 h:PN Mahalo no ka mea ʻono kuki o Kauaʻi.  Aloha.  A hui hou.\n07:54 h:h1 A hui hou nō.\n07:56  Nani Kauaʻi\n  > Aloha aʻe au i kuʻu ʻāina\n  I ke kūkilakila ʻo Waiʻaleʻale\n\n  Aloha aʻe au i kuʻu ʻāina\n  I ke kūkilakila ʻo Waiʻaleʻale\n\n  ʻO ke one kaulana aʻo Nohili\n  Ipo iho paʻa pono lā i kou poli\n\n  ʻO ke one kaulana aʻo Nohili\n  Ipo iho paʻa pono lā i kou poli\n\n  Nā hala onaona a Māpuana\n  E naue ē i ka ʻoni a ke kai\n\n  Nā hala onaona a Māpuana\n  E naue ē i ka ʻoni a ke kai\n\n  Hāʻina ʻia mai ana ka puana\n  Ua nani Kauaʻi i ka mālie\n\n  Hāʻina ʻia mai ana ka puana\n  Ua nani Kauaʻi i ka mālie\n\n10:27 h:HB A girlʻs mokihana lei initiated the previous discussion on the island of Kauaʻi.  She and her friend talked about areas she had visited such as Kōkeʻe, Waimea, Hāʻena, Poʻipū, Hanalei, and Wailua.  Her friend had also been to Kauaʻi and seemed to find Kīlauea especially interesting.  The accompanying songs both dealt with the island.\n10:51 h:h1 Ka Pua Kolū:\n Auē.  Nui ka ʻeha.  He kukū i loko o kuʻu wāwae.  \n10:59 h:NA Aia i hea ke kukū?\n11:01 h:h1 Ma ʻaneʻi.  Ma lalo o kuʻu wāwae hema.\n11:04 h:NA Ma hea lā.  Nui ka lepo ma kou wāwae.\n11:08 h:h1 Eia nō.  E nānā ʻoe.\n11:10 h:NA {A.}  Ke ʻike nei au i ke kukū.  Makemake ʻoe iaʻu e huki a wehe i ke kukū mai kou wāwae mai?\n11:19 h1 E ʻoluʻolu ʻoe.  Mālama pono.  Auī.\n11:23 h:NA Eia ke kukū.  Nui kēia kukū a kapakahi nō hoʻi.\n11:28 h1 He wāwae lūʻau koʻu.  Hilahila au.\n11:31 h:NA ʻAʻole.  He wāwae uʻi kou e like me Cinderella.\n11:36 h1 He aha ke ʻano o kēia kukū?\n11:39 h:NA He kukū kolū kēnā.\n11:41 h:h1 ʻO ia.  Eia ka lāʻau.  Pupuka.  Nui nā kukū.\n11:46 h:NA ʻAʻole pololei.  E nānā ʻoe i nā pua.\n11:50 h1 {A.}  Nani loa.  Ua like me kuʻu lei hulu melemele.\n11:55 h:NA ʻAe.  E hanu iho ʻoe.\n11:58 h1 ʻAʻala.\n11:59 h:NA E ʻako kāua i kekahi.\n12:02  Ka Pua Kolū Nani Loa\n  > Ua ʻike aʻe nei au i ka nani o ka pua kolū\n  Melemele kohu hulu manu, palupalu ke ʻike aku\n\n  Ua ʻike aʻe nei au i ka nani o ka pua kolū\n  Melemele kohu hulu manu, palupalu ke ʻike aku\n\n  Nā kukū e ʻoi ana hōʻehaʻeha i ka lima lā\n  I ka hele ʻana a kokoke o ka mea hoʻohihi i ka uʻi\n\n  Nā kukū e ʻoi ana hōʻehaʻeha i ka lima lā\n  I ka hele ʻana a kokoke o ka mea hoʻohihi i ka uʻi\n\n  Loaʻa ka pua kūpaoa, paʻa naʻe ʻoe i ke kukū\n  ʻO ka pua mae koke wale, ʻaʻole ʻoe e pakele aku\n\n  Loaʻa ka pua kūpaoa, paʻa naʻe ʻoe i ke kukū\n  ʻO ka pua mae koke wale, ʻaʻole ʻoe e pakele aku\n \n  Hāʻina ʻia mai ka puana no ka pua kolū nani loa\n  Hele nō ʻoe a kokoke, paʻa ʻaʻole pakele\n\n  Hāʻina ʻia mai ka puana no ka pua kolū nani loa\n  Hele nō ʻoe a kokoke, paʻa ʻaʻole pakele\n\n14:43 h:HB The short dialogue you just heard was about the kolū flower and its thorns which pricked the feet of a girl.  At first, she isn''t impressed by the kolū bush because it isn''t pretty.  But after her friend shows her the flower which is indeed pretty and very fragrant, she changes her mind.  The music and words of the accompanying song, Ka Pua Kolū Nani Loa were written by members of the Hui Aloha ʻĀina Tuahine.  It took third prize in the Parks and Recreation Song Contest._\n15:18 LK Welina o ke aloha, e nā ʻōiwi, nā kupa o ka ʻāina me nā makamaka o kēia ahiahi.  E maliu mai ʻoukou i ka uea o kēia kahua hoʻolele leo.  E hon^^ e honehone ana i ko kākou ʻōlelo aloha o ka ʻāina.  Eia me kākou i kēia ahiahi, ko kākou hoa kipa, ʻo Reverend Louis Kaulanaʻula Grace.  Aloha nō e Louis.\n15:44 LG Aloha.\n15:46 LK ʻAe.  I hea ʻoe i hānau ʻia ai?\n15:49 LG Hānau ʻia au ma Nāpoʻopoʻo, Kona Hema.  A hānai ʻia ma Keʻei e koʻu makua kāne hānai.\n15:58 LK A ʻo wai ka inoa o kou kupun^^ a, kou makua kāne hānai?\n16:02 LG ʻO Louis Pānui koʻu makua kāne hānai.\n16:05 LK ʻAe.  A i.\n16:06 LG Kaikunāne no koʻu makuahine.\n16:09 LK ʻAe.  A ʻo wai kou mau mākua?\n16:11 LG Koʻu makuahine, ʻo Kamakaʻōpiopio.  ʻO koʻu makua kāne ʻo Keoni Kalē, ka ^^^ ʻōlelo Hawaiʻi a ʻo John Grace hoʻi ma ka ʻōlelo haole.\n16:22 LK ʻAe. ^^^\n16:23 LG ^^^\n16:24 LK A i ka makahiki hea ʻoe i hānau ʻi^^ i hānau ʻia ai?\n16:28 LG Hānau wau^^ ʻia au i ka makahiki ʻumikūmāiwa haneli, Malaki ʻumikūmākolu.\n16:34 LK ʻAe.  A pehea ka lōkihi o kou noho ʻana i, i Oʻahu nei?\n16:41 LG {A,} i ka makahiki ʻumikumamāiwa kanakolukūmāwau^^ walu wau i hoʻi mai ai i Oʻahu nei a hiki i kēia manawa.\n16:49 LK ʻAe.\n16:49 LG ʻUmikūmāiwa kanahikukūmālua, kokoke kanahā makahiki.\n16:55 LK ʻAe.\n16:55 LG ʻOi kanahākūmālua.\n16:57 LK ʻAe.\n16:57 LG {Mū, mū.}\n16:58 LK A pehea kāu hana i kēia manawa?\n17:02 LG A ua hoʻomaha au me ka hana mai, mai ka hui wai.  A kaʻu hana i kēia manawa, unuhi i ka ʻōlelo haole i ka ʻōlelo Hawaiʻi, a, no ka nūpepa Ka Hoaaloha no nā ekalesia Hawaiʻi a puni kēia mokuʻāina.\n17:20 LK ʻAe.  Mahalo wau iā ʻoe i kou unuhi ʻana, no ka mea, ua ʻike liʻiliʻi wau i kāu hana, a he maikaʻi nō.  Mahalo nui iā ʻoe i ka hoʻomau ʻana ko kākou ʻōlelo makuahine.  ʻAe.\n17:37 LG Mahalo iā ʻoukou ko ʻoukou kono ʻana mai iaʻu e hele mai i ka KCCN.\n17:44 LK ʻAe.  ʻAʻohe pilikia.\n17:46 LK A.  Pehea ka hana a nā kahu hānai i kou wā ʻōpiopio?\n17:52 LG A koʻu wā ʻōpiopio, koʻu hele ʻana i ke kula aupuni, koʻu kumu ia ʻike ai i ka ʻōlelo makuahine, ʻōlelo Hawaiʻi.  I nā manawa a pau, a e pau ai ke kula, koʻu hoʻi ʻana mai ma ka home, nīnau mau ana lāua, koʻu mau mākua kāne, koʻu makua kāne hānai me koʻu makuahine hānai, "He aha ka moʻolelo" i ʻōlelo mai, "i aʻo ʻia mai nei ʻoe i kēia lā?"  Kekahi manawa, hahaʻi akula wau, "A moʻolelo pili ana no Kāwika me Gōlia, ka pilikua."  A kā lākou, kā lāua ʻōlelo mua iaʻu, "E huli ʻoe i loko o ka Paipala.  Ma laila i wehewehe ʻia ai ka moʻolelo o Kāwika me Kōlia."  ʻO ia koʻu kumu, huli i ka Paipala.  ʻIke au i ka ʻōlelo makuahine ma ka hoʻokuʻikuʻi ʻana i ka ʻōlelo a hiki iaʻu ke opuna^^ hoʻopuka pono a maopopo iaʻu ka manaʻo o ka ʻōlelo.  Pēlā ^^^ au i kula ai iaʻu iho,\n18:47 LK ʻĒ.\n18:47 LG ma ka ʻōlelo makuahine,\n18:48 LK ʻAe.\n18:48 LG ka ʻōlelo Hawaiʻi.\n18:50 LK ʻEhia nā hale pule ma kou ʻāina ma Keʻei, ma Nāpoʻopoʻo?\n18:55 LG  A ma Nāpoʻopoʻo, he hoʻokahi wale nō ekalesia ma Kona.  A ma, a, Kainaliu, hoʻokahi.  A ka ekalesia makua o Kona, ʻo ia ʻo Mokuʻaikaua.\n19:07 LK ʻAe.\n19:07 LG Aia ma Kona ʻĀkau.\n19:08 LK A pehea ʻo kēia hale pule ʻo Kahikolu?\n19:12 LG Kahikolu.  ʻO ia koʻu ekalesia.  A kēia manawa, a, ua nahā ka ekalesia kahiko, a ua hoʻihoʻi lākou i ka eke^^, ekalesia ma kahakai.\n19:23 LK ʻĒ.\n19:24 LG A ma laila ʻo Kahikolu i kēia.\n19:25 LK ʻAʻohe hale pule o Keʻei?\n19:27 LG ʻAʻole.  ʻAʻohe hale pule o Keʻei.\n19:29 LK ʻAe.\n19:29 LG Ua hele nā hoahānau o Keʻei i Nāpoʻopoʻo i Kahikolu,\n19:33 LK ʻAe.\n19:34 LG i ka pule.\n19:35 LK E kala mai.  E hoʻolaha ana au i ka helu kelepona o kēia kahua hoʻolele.  A iā ʻoukou, e nā mea e hoʻolohe mai ana i kēia ahiahi.  Inā he manaʻo paha ko ʻoukou, a he nīnau paha kā ʻoukou, e kole^^ e kelepona mai.  A eia ka helu, ka helu ʻeiwa ʻelua ʻekolu, ʻole ʻehā ʻole ʻehā.  Ka helu ʻeiwa ʻelua ʻekolu, ʻole ʻehā ʻole ʻekolu, a me ka helu ʻeiwa ʻelua ʻekolu, ʻole ʻehā ʻole ʻelua.  He, he ʻāina nui ke kanaka o Keʻei?\n20:17 LG Ma mua, i koʻu manawa, nui i ke kānaka o Keʻei.  Nui.\n20:21 LK ʻAe.  Ha,\n20:22 LG Mai ka kahakai a hiki o uka o Keʻei, ua piha i ke kānaka.\n20:26 LK ʻAe.   \n20:26 LG A ma hope mai, a hele liʻiliʻi, make nō hoʻi.  Hapa nui, hoʻi mai kekahi i Honolulu.\n20:34 LK {Mū.}\n20:34 LG Kēia manawa, kākaʻikahi ke kānaka o Keʻei.\n20:37 LK ʻAe.  A ʻo wai nā 